abstract: While Democrats and Republicans debate whether he should be convicted and removed from office, the president has offered up an alternative menu of events and priorities.
snippet: While Democrats and Republicans debate whether he should be convicted and removed from office, the president has offered up an alternative menu of events and priorities.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On the chilly grounds of the National Mall, within sight of the gleaming white Capitol where he is on trial for high crimes and misdemeanors, President Trump on Friday rallied abortion opponents gathered for their annual march and equated their battle with his own.

headline_main: Trump Tries to Upstage Drama in the Senate With His Own Programming
headline_print_headline: President Tries to Upstage Drama in Senate With His Own Programming

abstract: At a hearing in late September, the lawmaker portrayed “the essence” of the real call by pretending the president was a mobster shaking someone down.
snippet: At a hearing in late September, the lawmaker portrayed “the essence” of the real call by pretending the president was a mobster shaking someone down.
lead_paragraph: Representative Adam B. Schiff, the lead House manager, for the first time took head-on the Republican criticism that he mocked President Trump during a hearing by pretending the president’s call with his Ukrainian counterpart was a mob shakedown.
headline_main: Schiff addresses criticism over his imitation of the president.

abstract: The lawmaker implored senators not to set a precedent that would cede Congress’s investigative authority to the executive branch for generations to come.
snippet: The lawmaker implored senators not to set a precedent that would cede Congress’s investigative authority to the executive branch for generations to come.
lead_paragraph: In his closing remarks, Representative Adam Schiff of California, the chairman of the House Intelligence Committee, outlined a dire warning: that a failure to reprove President Trump for obstructing Congress would inflict “an unending injury to this country” because “the balance of power that our founders set out will never be the same.”
headline_main: Schiff warns that not removing Trump would be ‘an unending injury’ to U.S.

abstract: Representative Adam B. Schiff took a risk in telling senators they must convict and remove President Trump because “you know you can't trust this president to do what's right for this country.”
snippet: Representative Adam B. Schiff took a risk in telling senators they must convict and remove President Trump because “you know you can't trust this president to do what's right for this country.”
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator James M. Inhofe, a conservative Republican from Oklahoma, has made clear that he intends to vote to acquit President Trump. But after Representative Adam B. Schiff’s fiery speech Thursday night calling for the president’s removal, Mr. Inhofe felt compelled to give his fellow lawmaker some grudging respect.

headline_main: Emotional Schiff Speech Goes Viral, Delighting the Left and Enraging the Right
headline_print_headline: Fiery Speech Delights Left, Enrages Right

abstract: Some have been cheered again by admirers while others are drawing a new round of insults and invective from supporters of Mr. Trump — and even from the president himself.
snippet: Some have been cheered again by admirers while others are drawing a new round of insults and invective from supporters of Mr. Trump — and even from the president himself.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Admirers still stop and thank them on the street and in airports, send fan mail and sometimes even offer to pay for their meals. But supporters of President Trump still insult and threaten them online — even the ones who work in the White House.

headline_main: In Limelight Again, Key Impeachment Witnesses Still Experience a Divided Response
headline_print_headline: Investigation Witnesses Are Celebrated, and Denounced, for Speaking Out
byline_original: By Michael Crowley and Julian E. Barnes

abstract: Does equality in the age of Trump mean I can be irrationally angry, too?
snippet: Does equality in the age of Trump mean I can be irrationally angry, too?
lead_paragraph: The president’s freewheeling racism, emanating year after year from the top of the American political order, has made me more hostile toward white folks and whiteness than I’ve ever been in my life. Despite the fact that I’ve written provocatively (so I’m told) about racial matters for years, this hostility is new — and I’m increasingly unafraid to express it.

abstract: Representative Jason Crow of Colorado told senators that the goal of impeachment was to “protect against future presidential misconduct that would endanger democracy and the rule of law.”
snippet: Representative Jason Crow of Colorado told senators that the goal of impeachment was to “protect against future presidential misconduct that would endanger democracy and the rule of law.”
lead_paragraph: As they wrap up their case, House managers have one final task: Prove that President Trump is a future threat, not just a past one.

abstract: From the floor of the Senate, Democratic impeachment prosecutors said Friday that President Donald Trump tried to cover up his actions with Ukraine, another reason to remove him from office.
snippet: From the floor of the Senate, Democratic impeachment prosecutors said Friday that President Donald Trump tried to cover up his actions with Ukraine, another reason to remove him from office.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — From the floor of the Senate, Democratic impeachment prosecutors said Friday that President Donald Trump tried to cover up his actions with Ukraine, another reason to remove him from office.
headline_main: Trial Highlights: Dems Cry Cover-Up, Trump Hails Activists
headline_print_headline: Trial Highlights: Dems Cry Cover-Up, Trump Hails Activists

abstract: The House managers rest their case. For now.
snippet: The House managers rest their case. For now.
lead_paragraph: Friday was crunch time for the House managers in the Senate’s impeachment trial of President Trump. It was their third and final day of opening arguments — which, to review, in most trials would be merely the start of their case. But in these jury-rigged proceedings, run by a Republican Senate leadership keen to block witnesses and other evidence in the rush toward what most expect to be a precooked acquittal, opening arguments may be as good as it gets for the prosecution.

abstract: A reporter for NPR recounted that the secretary of state shouted at her, using an expletive and demanding, “Do you think Americans care about Ukraine?”
snippet: A reporter for NPR recounted that the secretary of state shouted at her, using an expletive and demanding, “Do you think Americans care about Ukraine?”
lead_paragraph: As the hearing was underway, Secretary of State Mike Pompeo got into it with a reporter for NPR, Mary Louise Kelly, after she asked about his failure to stand up for the former ambassador to Ukraine, Marie L. Yovanovitch. Ms. Kelly reported that Mr. Pompeo shouted at her, using an expletive and demanding, “Do you think Americans care about Ukraine?”
headline_main: Pompeo lashes out at reporter over Ukraine questions.
